english:
  title: A Letter to Reverent Master Joon
  author: Gang Seok-deok
  language: eng
  text: |-
    I, Ziming, bow respectfully before the seat of Reverent Master Joon of Heungseong at Ogwan Mountain and present this letter.

    Word has reached me that the venerable monk Seokhbong is in good health, steadfast in his recitation of the Buddha's name. From afar, I send my congratulations and warm wishes.

    Previously, imagining you alone in the quiet mountains, I ventured to offer some rough verses as a small jest—never daring to expect a reply. Yet you have honored me with words both earnest and refined, showing compassion even to one so unworthy as myself. I am deeply grateful. Still, your praise exceeds what I deserve—I cannot accept such kind words, I truly cannot.

    Though I have become an official, I have always kept my heart with the teachings of Confucius and Mencius, devoted to the study of classics and poetry. I am not like the elder masters, those enlightened laypeople who have surrendered their hearts to deep meditation and devoted themselves to studying the Buddhist scriptures. Yet in my youth, I spent time dwelling at a temple, and in the intervals between my studies there, I often conversed with monks and grasped some fragments of their teachings. Today I venture to share with you what little I understand.

    The sutras say: "Quietly raising the Patriarch's Chan, leisurely observing the Buddha's teachings, with remaining energy chanting Amitabha, seeking rebirth in the Pure Land." These are words of truth, without deception. Following this, I have made it my ultimate concern, my fundamental koan.

    Yet I humbly wonder—if the Mirror of the Doctrine truly takes the contemplation of Buddha and study of teachings as the ultimate, why does it not place these two practices above the peaceful Chan itself? And what does it mean by "leisurely observing" and "remaining energy"? According to the teachings of the sages, there is no Way outside the mind, and no mind outside the Way. If one does not perfect the work of investigation, extension of knowledge, sincerity of intention, and rectification of heart, how can one expect the fruits of self-cultivation, ordering the family, governing the state, and bringing peace to all under heaven?

    This is why those who follow the Buddha's way so often bring shame upon themselves—they fail to cultivate their own nature. Within the Buddha's teachings, there are both provisional and ultimate teachings. The Mirror's words, I fear, are not the ultimate truth but rather provisional expedients. Have you not heard the Patriarch say: "The very word 'Buddha' offends my ears; the Twelve-fold Teachings and Three Vehicles resound like a struck bell—yet the Chan school holds to only One Mind. Remove even this, and nothing else remains as truth"?

    Do you not recall what High Peak said of Chan meditation: "If you wish to accomplish realization by a certain date, it is like falling to the bottom of a thousand-foot well. You have only one thing—to seek a way out, to turn your heart toward escape. Where, in such practice, is there leisure to recite the Buddha's name or chant sutras?"

    Alas, the teachings of the masters have been so clearly transmitted! Yet people cling to expedients, refusing to turn their minds around, spending all their energy on superficial effort. How can they dare claim to have realized their fundamental nature? If one does not change such ways, like a stubborn donkey refusing to alter its course, when the final reckoning comes on the last day of the year—when one lies in the hospice of longevity, a solitary lamp casting shadows on the wall, snow falling from one's eyes—then neither Buddha's name nor sutras can be recited. The four mountains collapse. Like a crab dropped into boiling water. Like an old demon receiving blows from an iron staff—regret comes too late.

    There are also base creatures of this world, lacking in conduct and honor, doing whatever taboos forbid, flattering the powerful, grasping for position through cunning. Their wickedness knows no bounds. And there are shaven-headed monks in their dark robes who have abandoned the precepts entirely, clever only in debate, never having done true practice. Then one day their hair turns white, their teeth yellow. Looking back at their lives, they find nothing gained. Only then do they begin to recite the Buddha's name, chant sutras, seeking the Western Paradise to erase their karma. Are they not exactly like those base creatures?

    The ancient worthy said: "A true man holds ambitions that pierce the sky, yet refuses to walk the path the Buddha walked." A great man—if he will not walk even where the Tathagata walks, how could he bear to set foot on the petty paths of lesser beings?

    I beseech you, Reverend Master: Take what you call the ultimate fundamental koan, bind it tight, cast it toward other worlds, and never look back. Throughout the twelve hours of the day, sit upright upon your meditation cushion, straighten your spine, and simply raise this one question: "What is this Pure Land of mind? What is this Amitabha of original nature?" Back and forth, pressing harder and harder—the mind grows more confused, more muddled, until finally there is nowhere left to apply force. Then one morning, suddenly, all worldly delusions fall away. Your whole body breaks into sweat. In that moment, Amitabha and the Pure Land manifest of themselves—is this not sublime beyond measure? This Buddha-remembrance far surpasses the mechanical recitation of old.

    I pick up the brush to write this, yet entanglements abound. Let me set this aside. Much remains unsaid.

    This Twenty-first Day of the Wuchen Year of the Zhengtong Era,
    Bowing respectfully,
    Gang Ziming, Wandering Scholar of the Pines,
    From Jinyang
